@astroeringrand @nj_tierney @kara_woo TIPS: If you restart #rstats often and you want to limit these to appear at most once an hour, do:

> startup::install()

Then put these quoting calls in a file:

~/.Rprofile.d/quotes,interactive=TRUE,when=hourly.R

That's it

Now I realized how this was rather cavalier, especially without context (which I briefly explained here). My intent was not to diminish the great achievements of a few people in the #rstats spatial world (they will recognize themselves), but… 13/

My background is in movement ecology — that sets up the scene, and certainly explains my biases and shortcomings. I have been working primarily in #rstats for almost 20 years, rapidly working with #adehabitat and then #sp to solve spatial ecology problems. 2/

Without a second thought, I contacted all movement experts I know and suggested the idea of the #rstats Spatial Working Group (RSWG), basically scaling up a need from the movement world. This ended up as a public discussion on r-spatial on GitHub: 12/

https://t.co/2Y0R0G3uFt

With time, I contributed to a growing ecosystem, through my involvement in #adehabitatHS, or my own packages #hab or #rpostgis. I have been amazed by the progress and flourishing development of spatial #rstats packages, but also frustrated at times. 3/

https://t.co/kqgCO4Wl75

With all this said, back to my initial tweet, and the proposition to start a #rstats Spatial Working Group within the @RConsortium. My own experience within the movement world showed me a lack of shared governance and directions within our community (again, movement). 10/

So it seems I caused a few unexpected waves that may be a bit too high for me. I recently contacted a bunch of #movement experts about the idea of an #rstats Spatial Working Group within the @RConsortium, and now would be a good time to explain. A thread. 1/ https://t.co/TydLTAXBCK

1) @rocio_joo led a review of #rstats packages for tracking data (x, y, z, t). We listed and described 58 R tracking packages (as of August 2018) explicitly developed to either create/transform/analyze tracking data. 5/

For #rstats beginners like me. subsetting a df by a logical variable[TRUE/FALSE] tip: subset(df, logic var) will give you all data where the var is TRUE. If you want only FALSE, then subset(df, logic var==FALSE) or logic var !=TRUE. the double == is crucial. Better suggestions?

Starting a thread on #rstats #r4ds for brainstorming how to teacher R to first timers.   First - use @rstudio cloud , which was free for educators last year.  1/

My biggest worry for moving intro #rstats courses online is helping students learn to spot errors eg missing commas.  I think I am going to develop “pin the comma on the broken script” type exercises. Missing , ( [ and = in arguments really grind new users down 5/
Rstudio cloud has a number of good tutorials built in learnr which are good for beginners to #rstats  2/

I’ve been reminded that when teaching intro  #rstats dataviz helps keep students engaged  I really like teAching ggplot using ggpubr as a starting point.  This could be really important when courses move online 6/. H/t @BrandonHoenig
A popular exercise is to have students build ugly graphs in #rstats.      Could be a good team project for when classes move online.  I know @gabbspalomo had some awesome submissions this spring 7/

For moving #rstats courses online I’m considering building Multiple choice and fill in the blanks exercises in our Learning management software @CanvasLMS student will get a script then answer questions & annotate code and enter answers into online assignment 6/

Am starting to plan for at least an online start to my #rstats course for undergrad biology.   Will use @rstudio cloud, but thinking how to manager all the basic annoyances like missing commas etc that new users face.  70 students, about 1/2 with no previous coding

A cool tool for intro #rstats is swirl.  Focus is on base R but cool stuff and IIRC lots of exercises available .  Very cool platform but labor intensive I need to look into it more as I face moving classes online 10/

Many students new to #rstats struggle with understanding their computers file system.  Using rstudio cloud helps, or a teaching package .  Directly loading or scraping data from online sources is easy too  8/

@dan_p_simpson @djnavarro It's easy to mistake R Core, CRAN, R Foundation, R Consortium, ... as a single entity - they're not. I'm still learning and have re-interpreted their different roles a few times during the two decades I've known #rstats /1

@dan_p_simpson @djnavarro The R Foundation (https://t.co/7VPWcwzQK5) supports (but doesn't organize) the useR! and DSC confs (https://t.co/kjTLJ6v9Oz). It's thxs to the RF Conf Committee we now have an official Code of Conduct - this is fairly recent in the history of #rstats /2

@dan_p_simpson @djnavarro Although intersecting with R Core, who founded the R Foundation [0], CRAN (\Comprehensive R Archive Network\") is technically its own entity outside of the RF umbrella (at least AFAIU) /3 #rstats [0] https://t.co/SJ3N6FqDhe"

!!! After struggling with mysterious missing #rstats data for hours, I just learned that #dplyr::filter drops NA's, even with a != condition. So df %>% filter(condition != \bad\") removes rows with condition == \"bad\" AND rows with https://t.co/9i4Kwr5Rbl(condition). 1/3"
